WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.005 --> 00:00:09.009
( intro music )

00:00:12.878 --> 00:00:15.214
<i> This isn't a religious war.</i>

00:00:15.214 --> 00:00:18.318
<i>It's a war whose roots are based</i>

00:00:18.318 --> 00:00:20.186
<i> in poverty, corruption.</i>

00:00:20.953 --> 00:00:23.622
<i> Central African Republic
 for a time</i>

00:00:23.622 --> 00:00:25.125
<i> went psychotic.</i>

00:00:26.425 --> 00:00:29.395
( applause )

00:00:29.395 --> 00:00:31.263
Peter Gwin:
You know here we have a country

00:00:31.263 --> 00:00:33.967
that has 4.5 million people.

00:00:33.967 --> 00:00:36.635
<i> It's a little bit smaller
 than the state of Texas.</i>

00:00:36.635 --> 00:00:40.106
<i> It's 85 percent Christian
or traditional animist beliefs.</i>

00:00:40.106 --> 00:00:42.808
<i> And 15 percent identifies
 as Muslim.</i>

00:00:42.808 --> 00:00:45.645 line:0%
But here's how the people in the
Central African Republic

00:00:45.645 --> 00:00:46.612 line:0%
identify themselves.

00:00:46.812 --> 00:00:48.447
<i> I'm going to refer to the
 Central African Republic</i>

00:00:48.447 --> 00:00:50.816
<i> by the shorthand that we
 sort of all default to CAR,</i>

00:00:50.816 --> 00:00:53.820
<i> so if you are confused
that's what I am talking about.</i>

00:00:53.820 --> 00:00:57.189
<i> This is a map from
 a high school geography book.</i>

00:00:57.189 --> 00:00:59.391
<i>And it shows the ethnic groups.</i>

00:00:59.391 --> 00:01:02.027
<i> And there are more than 50
 ethnic groups and sub-groups.</i>

00:01:02.027 --> 00:01:05.464
<i> It's also a nation filled with
 treasure literally.</i>

00:01:05.464 --> 00:01:07.400
<i>Fairly famous for its diamonds.</i>

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:09.201
<i> One of the biggest diamonds
 ever found,</i>

00:01:09.201 --> 00:01:12.205
<i> almost 400 carats
 was found in the CAR.</i>

00:01:12.205 --> 00:01:13.673
<i> It also has gold mines.</i>

00:01:13.673 --> 00:01:17.677
<i> Both of these resources are
 mined using artisanal methods,</i>

00:01:17.677 --> 00:01:19.845
<i> that means it's not
 an industrial scale thing.</i>

00:01:19.845 --> 00:01:22.749
It's all like open-pit mine,
digging like that.

00:01:22.749 --> 00:01:25.485
<i> In recent years,
 petroleum has been found</i>

00:01:25.485 --> 00:01:27.854
<i> up near the Chad border.</i>

00:01:27.854 --> 00:01:30.756
And, there's also
deposits of uranium.

00:01:30.756 --> 00:01:33.493
France's first atomic weapon
came from uranium

00:01:33.493 --> 00:01:35.495
that was mined in the CAR.

00:01:35.495 --> 00:01:39.031
It also has huge reserves of
timber, game animals,

00:01:39.031 --> 00:01:43.135
but also the potential
for hydropower.

00:01:43.135 --> 00:01:44.604
So what went wrong?
What happened?

00:01:44.604 --> 00:01:47.139
Usually this is
the equation for...

00:01:47.139 --> 00:01:48.141
for prosperity, right?

00:01:48.141 --> 00:01:50.877
You have a fairly
good-sized country,

00:01:50.877 --> 00:01:53.879
with a relatively
small population

00:01:53.879 --> 00:01:56.348
and all these resources.
So, you know,

00:01:56.348 --> 00:01:58.518
why are we where we are today?

00:01:58.518 --> 00:02:02.188
<i> And a lot of the answer has to
 lie at the feet of these men.</i>

00:02:02.188 --> 00:02:03.989
<i> These are the six leaders</i>

00:02:03.989 --> 00:02:06.358
<i>of the Central African Republic
 since independence.</i>

00:02:06.358 --> 00:02:08.895
<i> This is a monument in Bangui.</i>

00:02:08.895 --> 00:02:10.797
<i> It was erected in 2008,</i>

00:02:10.797 --> 00:02:13.332
<i> which was the 50th anniversary
 of independence.</i>

00:02:13.332 --> 00:02:16.835
<i> And each person on each
 one of these gold busts</i>

00:02:16.835 --> 00:02:18.971
<i> betrayed one of the
 guys up here.</i>

00:02:18.971 --> 00:02:21.273
<i> The guy that takes
 the cake of the leaders</i>

00:02:21.273 --> 00:02:23.375
<i> in terms of driving
 the country into the ground</i>

00:02:23.375 --> 00:02:26.011
<i> is this guy,
 Jean-Bédel Bokassa.</i>

00:02:26.011 --> 00:02:28.013
<i> He was the president for life</i>

00:02:28.013 --> 00:02:29.916
<i> and then decided that
 wasn't a grand enough title,</i>

00:02:29.916 --> 00:02:32.017
<i> so he decided to
 become the Emperor</i>

00:02:32.017 --> 00:02:34.353
<i> of the Central African Empire.</i>

00:02:34.353 --> 00:02:35.922
<i> He was going to rename
 the whole country.</i>

00:02:35.922 --> 00:02:38.925
<i> He styled himself sort
 of the Napoleon of Africa.</i>

00:02:38.925 --> 00:02:42.294
And in an era when we saw
Muammar Gaddafi rise,

00:02:42.294 --> 00:02:44.296
Idi Amin was in his day,

00:02:44.296 --> 00:02:46.632
Mobutu Sese Seko was there,

00:02:46.632 --> 00:02:49.635
Bokassa gives them
all a run for their money.

00:02:49.635 --> 00:02:53.572
He actually met his nadir when

00:02:53.572 --> 00:02:55.408
he decreed that
all school children

00:02:55.408 --> 00:02:58.110
had to buy their school
uniforms from his,

00:02:58.110 --> 00:02:59.779
a company that he owned.

00:02:59.779 --> 00:03:02.215
And when they had...
a rebellion,

00:03:02.215 --> 00:03:03.482
when there was a protest,

00:03:03.482 --> 00:03:05.784
he had a hundred of
them arrested,

00:03:05.784 --> 00:03:07.386
many were beaten, some killed

00:03:07.386 --> 00:03:08.855
and that was sort
of the moment that he...

00:03:08.855 --> 00:03:10.289
he met his downfall.

00:03:11.057 --> 00:03:12.691
<i> Another issue
 that's been happening</i>

00:03:12.691 --> 00:03:14.160
<i> over the past 10 years or so,</i>

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:17.229
<i> more than that but 10 years is
really the area that we focus on</i>

00:03:17.229 --> 00:03:19.198
<i> is poaching the game.</i>

00:03:19.198 --> 00:03:21.433
<i> And specifically
 the forest elephants.</i>

00:03:21.433 --> 00:03:23.936
Poachers have been
coming to the CAR

00:03:23.936 --> 00:03:27.373
mostly from Sudan
in organized fashion.

00:03:27.373 --> 00:03:28.975
Many of these are Janjaweed.

00:03:28.975 --> 00:03:30.809
In fact one man described
it to me

00:03:30.809 --> 00:03:33.346
as "it's an ivory bank account".

00:03:33.346 --> 00:03:36.315
We just come when
we need money.

00:03:36.315 --> 00:03:37.283
In the past ten years,

00:03:37.450 --> 00:03:41.020
I think they estimate
5,500 elephants have been killed

00:03:41.020 --> 00:03:43.422
for their ivory.

00:03:43.422 --> 00:03:45.891
And that's about 62 percent
of the population.

00:03:45.891 --> 00:03:48.628
So,
only about 30 percent remain.

00:03:50.463 --> 00:03:53.332
<i> The Séléka are a
 group of militias</i>

00:03:53.332 --> 00:03:55.835
<i> predominantly from the north,
 Muslim based.</i>

00:03:55.835 --> 00:04:00.606
<i> And funded by Chad to come and
 fight the Bozizé government.</i>

00:04:00.606 --> 00:04:03.776
<i> They were opposed
 by the anti-balaka,</i>

00:04:03.810 --> 00:04:07.713
<i> begun as a sort of a local
 neighborhood security force.</i>

00:04:07.713 --> 00:04:09.415
<i> When the Séléka rose up,</i>

00:04:09.415 --> 00:04:10.716
<i> these guys organized,</i>

00:04:10.716 --> 00:04:12.651
<i> they realized they needed
 some protection.</i>

00:04:12.651 --> 00:04:14.020
<i> Once the Séléka were gone</i>

00:04:14.020 --> 00:04:17.590
<i> they took out reprisals on
 the Muslim population.</i>

00:04:17.590 --> 00:04:19.291
<i> They committed many
 of the same atrocities</i>

00:04:19.291 --> 00:04:20.993
<i> the Séléka had committed.</i>

00:04:20.993 --> 00:04:23.028
So that's not the
whole story though.

00:04:23.028 --> 00:04:25.531
<i>That's just what's happening in</i>

00:04:25.531 --> 00:04:27.433
<i> predominantly the East
 and the North of the country.</i>

00:04:27.433 --> 00:04:30.769
<i> There's another conflict
 that's going on-- far away,</i>

00:04:30.769 --> 00:04:33.372
<i> in the far eastern corner</i>

00:04:33.372 --> 00:04:35.107
<i>is a little village called Obo.</i>

00:04:35.107 --> 00:04:37.643
<i> It's a village of
 about 6,000 people.</i>

00:04:37.643 --> 00:04:41.079
<i> In Obo,
 we don't have the Séléka,</i>

00:04:41.079 --> 00:04:44.283
<i> we don't have concerns
 about anti-balaka.</i>

00:04:44.283 --> 00:04:48.086
<i> These are both Muslim and
 Christian children playing.</i>

00:04:48.086 --> 00:04:52.091
<i> These children are also under
 threat from another place.</i>

00:04:52.091 --> 00:04:54.661
<i> And that is,
 remember this guy?</i>

00:04:54.661 --> 00:04:57.063
<i> Joseph Kony rose to fame
 a couple of years ago,</i>

00:04:57.063 --> 00:04:59.765
<i> with the Kony 2012 video
 that went viral.</i>

00:04:59.765 --> 00:05:01.234
<i> For those of you
 who don't know the story,</i>

00:05:01.234 --> 00:05:02.868
<i> he is a Ugandan warlord</i>

00:05:02.868 --> 00:05:05.537
<i> who for the better part
 of the last two decades</i>

00:05:05.537 --> 00:05:08.240
has been kidnapping children

00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:10.009
to fight in his guerilla army

00:05:10.009 --> 00:05:14.814
and he sort of moved from
South Sudan to the DRC,

00:05:14.814 --> 00:05:17.950
and now he's found his way

00:05:17.950 --> 00:05:21.120
into the
Central African Republic.

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:24.524
And, especially given
the security situation

00:05:24.524 --> 00:05:28.127
that we have been
facing in CAR

00:05:28.127 --> 00:05:30.463
over the past year or so,

00:05:30.463 --> 00:05:33.398
his forces have moved,
you know,

00:05:33.398 --> 00:05:35.534
more forcefully into this area.

00:05:35.534 --> 00:05:38.070
But what's keeping
the people in Obo

00:05:38.070 --> 00:05:40.273
safe for the moment--

00:05:40.940 --> 00:05:42.575
is your tax dollars.

00:05:43.309 --> 00:05:45.378
<i> This is actually a
 Special Forces,</i>

00:05:45.378 --> 00:05:47.179
<i> US Special Forces base.</i>

00:05:47.179 --> 00:05:50.115
<i> It sits right on the
 corner of the village.</i>

00:05:50.115 --> 00:05:53.986
And the US has been there
for three years now, actually.

00:05:53.986 --> 00:05:57.122
In part providing security

00:05:57.122 --> 00:05:59.992
but in large part
training Ugandan troops

00:05:59.992 --> 00:06:03.563
and advising them on
tracking Kony and his...

00:06:03.563 --> 00:06:05.564
and his group.

00:06:05.564 --> 00:06:08.167
<i> So these are the Ugandan
 troops that they train.</i>

00:06:08.167 --> 00:06:10.102
<i> What's different
 apparently about this is</i>

00:06:10.102 --> 00:06:13.038
<i> that they are actually getting
 jungle war fighting training</i>

00:06:13.038 --> 00:06:16.775
<i> before they are sent actually
 to track Kony and his men.</i>

00:06:16.775 --> 00:06:18.777
And when I talk to people
in the village are they happy

00:06:18.777 --> 00:06:20.078
that these guys are here,
they said,

00:06:20.078 --> 00:06:23.282
if the United States
and Uganda wasn't here,

00:06:23.282 --> 00:06:26.218
Joseph Kony would be
sleeping in Obo tonight.

00:06:26.218 --> 00:06:29.554
But I understand human nature,
you want to put some faces,

00:06:29.554 --> 00:06:32.625
specific faces on these issues.

00:06:32.625 --> 00:06:34.327
So, I want to introduce you to
three people,

00:06:34.327 --> 00:06:38.730
so the next time you see
a random CAR news report

00:06:38.730 --> 00:06:41.767
or a 500-word AP story perhaps,

00:06:41.767 --> 00:06:44.736
you'll think of these
three people. So...

00:06:44.736 --> 00:06:48.241
<i>This is Aramis. He is from Obo.</i>

00:06:48.241 --> 00:06:50.842
<i> And he was kidnapped
 when he was 17 years old</i>

00:06:50.842 --> 00:06:52.811
<i> at his grandfather's house.</i>

00:06:52.811 --> 00:06:55.848
<i> And taken by the LRA
 into the jungle.</i>

00:06:55.848 --> 00:06:58.183
<i> He spent five years
 as a guerrilla fighter.</i>

00:06:58.183 --> 00:07:00.385
<i> He had horrible things
 done to him.</i>

00:07:00.385 --> 00:07:02.488
<i> And he did horrible things.</i>

00:07:03.288 --> 00:07:06.091
But he escaped about a year ago.

00:07:06.091 --> 00:07:10.362
And now he works with
the US and Ugandans

00:07:10.362 --> 00:07:14.433
to broadcast radio messages
into the jungle.

00:07:14.433 --> 00:07:17.036
And basically they are trying to
encourage the fighthers

00:07:17.036 --> 00:07:18.237
to give themselves up,

00:07:18.237 --> 00:07:20.205
just like Aramis did.

00:07:20.205 --> 00:07:23.208
And that's been a pretty
successful strategy.

00:07:23.208 --> 00:07:26.511
But so, once a week Aramis goes
into the radio station

00:07:26.511 --> 00:07:28.847
and basically talks to
his former comrades.

00:07:28.847 --> 00:07:30.949
And I sat in on
one of the sessions.

00:07:30.949 --> 00:07:33.385
And you know,
he calls them by name,

00:07:33.385 --> 00:07:36.389
he tells them, you know, your...

00:07:36.389 --> 00:07:37.823
you know,
your family wants you home.

00:07:37.823 --> 00:07:39.357
There's amnesty for anybody.

00:07:39.357 --> 00:07:40.892
The guys that they are really,

00:07:40.892 --> 00:07:43.262
basically going after
these days are Kony

00:07:43.262 --> 00:07:45.464
and the other leaders.

00:07:45.464 --> 00:07:49.368
<i> Another guy that I'd like you
 to meet is Albert.</i>

00:07:49.368 --> 00:07:52.538
<i> So, Albert I met on a trip
 this summer to Bangui.</i>

00:07:52.538 --> 00:07:56.175
<i> I'd barely gotten, you know,
 into the city and he was</i>

00:07:56.208 --> 00:08:00.045
<i> knocking on my door wanting to
 sell me something, you know.</i>

00:08:00.045 --> 00:08:02.681
He kept saying,
"I want you to buy
these pictures.

00:08:02.681 --> 00:08:04.716
I've got these great pictures."
And I was looking
at the pictures,

00:08:04.716 --> 00:08:06.718
like picture of a chicken,
you know,

00:08:06.718 --> 00:08:08.687
<i> "Man, do I really want
 a chicken picture?</i>

00:08:08.687 --> 00:08:10.022
( audience laughing )

00:08:10.022 --> 00:08:12.591
<i>And you know, I am sitting there
 looking at this thing</i>

00:08:12.591 --> 00:08:14.493
<i> and then I realized</i>

00:08:14.493 --> 00:08:18.397
<i> it's made out of
 butterfly wings.</i>

00:08:18.397 --> 00:08:20.432
<i> And I was blown away.</i>

00:08:20.432 --> 00:08:22.335
<i> So, he took me
 back to his workshop</i>

00:08:22.335 --> 00:08:23.368
<i> and he showed me
 how he does these.</i>

00:08:23.368 --> 00:08:25.738
<i> He collects these
 butterflies meticulously</i>

00:08:25.738 --> 00:08:30.242
<i> and makes these
 stained glass images of life</i>

00:08:30.242 --> 00:08:33.145
<i>in the Central African Republic.</i>

00:08:33.145 --> 00:08:35.581
<i> Boy climbing a tree.</i>

00:08:35.581 --> 00:08:38.050
<i> And this picture has
 special significance</i>

00:08:38.050 --> 00:08:40.252
<i> because it's his sister.</i>

00:08:40.252 --> 00:08:43.589
<i> And she was killed by
 the Séléka early this Spring.</i>

00:08:46.058 --> 00:08:48.494
Lastly, I want to
introduce you to the

00:08:48.494 --> 00:08:50.762
National Ballet of the
Central African Republic.

00:08:50.762 --> 00:08:52.565
They perform ethnic dances,

00:08:52.565 --> 00:08:53.865
so there's dancers
from all those

00:08:53.865 --> 00:08:56.168
ethnic communities
that I showed you.

00:08:56.168 --> 00:08:59.004
They are missing 14 of
their members since the violence

00:08:59.004 --> 00:09:01.340
and their rehearsal space
has been completely destroyed.

00:09:01.340 --> 00:09:04.610
So, they perform--

00:09:04.610 --> 00:09:07.713
They perform in a vacant lot
in downtown Bangui.

00:09:07.713 --> 00:09:11.250
And people just come and watch,
it's like free performances.

00:09:12.518 --> 00:09:13.852
<i> And I happened to come
 by one day</i>

00:09:13.852 --> 00:09:15.120
<i> when they were performing
 this piece,</i>

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:17.056
<i>which is actually a pygmy dance.</i>

00:09:17.056 --> 00:09:19.491
<i> And it tells the
 story of two women</i>

00:09:19.491 --> 00:09:22.627
<i> who are rivals for
 the affections of a man.</i>

00:09:22.627 --> 00:09:26.632
<i> And one of the women
 poisons her rival,</i>

00:09:26.632 --> 00:09:30.635
<i> and so an old healer is
 brought in</i>

00:09:30.635 --> 00:09:32.838
<i> to raise this woman
 from the dead.</i>

00:09:32.838 --> 00:09:35.040
<i> And this is the scene
 that you are going to see.</i>

00:09:35.040 --> 00:09:39.145
( singing in Sangho )

00:09:44.050 --> 00:09:50.056
( ethnic music )

00:10:06.738 --> 00:10:09.141
So, now I'm going to
pass it over to Marcus.

00:10:10.375 --> 00:10:14.547
( applause )

00:10:20.886 --> 00:10:22.988
Marcus Bleasdale:
Thanks, Peter, for that.

00:10:22.988 --> 00:10:25.324 line:0%
I think it's really
important to highlight

00:10:25.324 --> 00:10:29.061 line:0%
very early on in this
evening that

00:10:29.061 --> 00:10:31.797
this isn't a religious war.

00:10:31.797 --> 00:10:34.433
It's a war

00:10:34.433 --> 00:10:37.069
whose roots are based

00:10:37.069 --> 00:10:39.605
fundamentally in poverty.

00:10:39.605 --> 00:10:42.074
It's based in corruption.

00:10:42.074 --> 00:10:44.109
It's based in mismanagement,

00:10:44.109 --> 00:10:46.211
bad leadership,
many of which, you know,

00:10:46.211 --> 00:10:49.080
the leaders we were introduced
to through Peter tonight.

00:10:49.080 --> 00:10:52.117
And... religion has been used by

00:10:52.117 --> 00:10:54.987
the perpetrators to draw lines,

00:10:54.987 --> 00:10:59.758
to draw allegiances and
to try to create power.

00:10:59.758 --> 00:11:02.227
So, I think we should try to
rise above that this evening,

00:11:02.227 --> 00:11:04.229
and try to think in
a much more complex way

00:11:04.229 --> 00:11:07.099
about what is driving
this conflict.

00:11:07.099 --> 00:11:10.202
<i> What I'd like to do is
 to introduce you</i>

00:11:10.202 --> 00:11:13.171
<i> to the chronology
 of the conflict.</i>

00:11:13.171 --> 00:11:16.609
It started as we were
introduced to earlier on that

00:11:16.609 --> 00:11:19.111
the Séléka were funded by

00:11:19.111 --> 00:11:21.146
Idriss Deby, Chad
to come in and destabilize

00:11:21.146 --> 00:11:22.247
the Central African Republic,

00:11:22.247 --> 00:11:25.584
maybe take resources,
send those back to Chad

00:11:25.584 --> 00:11:28.621
but also destabilize the
Central African Republic,

00:11:28.621 --> 00:11:31.590
for the benefit of
its neighbors.

00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:34.793
And so this Séléka
group that was--

00:11:34.793 --> 00:11:36.629
that came into the country...

00:11:38.963 --> 00:11:41.099
attacked the then government,

00:11:41.099 --> 00:11:44.469
took power
from the government and...

00:11:44.469 --> 00:11:47.572
and then started to
rule over the population

00:11:47.572 --> 00:11:50.242
in a very authoritarian way.

00:11:50.242 --> 00:11:54.747
And the people who suffered
most under that very
early Séléka rule

00:11:54.747 --> 00:11:57.315
were the Christians.

00:11:57.315 --> 00:11:59.351
They were the ones that
