<i> The peacekeepers tried their
 best to keep the peace but...</i>

00:22:46.964 --> 00:22:48.232
<i>simply they couldn't control it,</i>

00:22:48.232 --> 00:22:49.200
<i>there weren't enough of them and</i>

00:22:49.333 --> 00:22:52.637
<i> the capital Bangui
 was completely out of control.</i>

00:22:52.637 --> 00:22:55.140
<i> The anti-balaka
 throughout the country,</i>

00:22:55.140 --> 00:22:57.408
<i> took control of whatever
 they could take control of</i>

00:22:57.408 --> 00:22:59.277
<i> and preyed on the
 remaining Muslims.</i>

00:22:59.277 --> 00:23:00.645
<i> They were trapped
 in these enclaves</i>

00:23:00.645 --> 00:23:02.914
<i> and they were picking
 them off one by one.</i>

00:23:03.914 --> 00:23:06.418
And so what did that lead to?

00:23:06.418 --> 00:23:08.753
Some people called
it ethnic cleansing.

00:23:08.753 --> 00:23:10.922
Amnesty international have
called it ethnic cleansing.

00:23:10.922 --> 00:23:12.891
What is ethnic cleansing?

00:23:12.891 --> 00:23:14.626
Ethnic cleansing is
where a group,

00:23:14.626 --> 00:23:17.428
a population are targeted,
very specific

00:23:17.428 --> 00:23:19.730
ethnic group are targeted by

00:23:19.730 --> 00:23:21.966
an organized group

00:23:21.966 --> 00:23:24.301
and it was very difficult
to say at the beginning whether

00:23:24.301 --> 00:23:25.736
the anti-balaka were organized?

00:23:25.736 --> 00:23:26.871
Whether they were coordinated?

00:23:26.871 --> 00:23:29.474
Whether there was
a chain of command?

00:23:29.474 --> 00:23:30.475
It's since been proved

00:23:30.709 --> 00:23:32.543
and they have admitted that
there is the chain of command

00:23:32.543 --> 00:23:34.045
within the anti-balaka.

00:23:34.045 --> 00:23:36.981
And so, maybe we can
call it ethnic cleansing.

00:23:36.981 --> 00:23:38.849
But really it's irrelevant
what we call it.

00:23:38.849 --> 00:23:41.953
Because the effect,
it was really the same.

00:23:41.953 --> 00:23:46.223
<i> This is a Chad Special Forces
 soldier coming into Bangui</i>

00:23:46.223 --> 00:23:48.526
<i> to escort tens of
 thousands of people</i>

00:23:48.526 --> 00:23:50.996
<i> out of the region on
 these trucks.</i>

00:23:50.996 --> 00:23:53.665
<i> I stood there for maybe
 45 minutes</i>

00:23:53.665 --> 00:23:56.467
<i> as truck after truck
 after truck loaded up</i>

00:23:56.467 --> 00:23:58.703
<i> to the extent that
 this one is loaded up,</i>

00:23:58.703 --> 00:24:01.273
<i> left Bangui with
 Muslims on board.</i>

00:24:02.240 --> 00:24:04.842
<i> This is a young
 father with a new born</i>

00:24:04.842 --> 00:24:08.780
<i> waiting for the trucks
 to leave the center of Bangui.</i>

00:24:08.780 --> 00:24:11.048
Many of these trucks
were targeted by anti-balaka

00:24:11.048 --> 00:24:13.952
on the road and grenades
were thrown into these trucks

00:24:13.952 --> 00:24:16.254
from the villages that
they were passing through.

00:24:16.254 --> 00:24:18.323
So not everybody
made it through.

00:24:18.323 --> 00:24:21.826
And the trip was hours,
days to...

00:24:21.826 --> 00:24:23.327
you know,
they were running the gauntlets

00:24:23.327 --> 00:24:24.495
of these anti-balaka groups

00:24:24.495 --> 00:24:26.832
for days to get
to Cameroon and Chad.

00:24:26.832 --> 00:24:29.634
<i> I recently visited most of the
 Peul population,</i>

00:24:29.634 --> 00:24:30.802
<i> hundreds of thousands
 of the people</i>

00:24:30.802 --> 00:24:32.437
<i> that are seeking
 refuge in Cameroon.</i>

00:24:32.437 --> 00:24:34.605
<i> For the first time in
 18 months they feel safe.</i>

00:24:34.605 --> 00:24:36.774
<i>For the first time in 18 months
 they have enough food.</i>

00:24:36.774 --> 00:24:38.242
<i> For the first time
 in a very long time</i>

00:24:38.242 --> 00:24:40.111
<i> they have shelter
 over their heads.</i>

00:24:40.111 --> 00:24:42.012
<i> Their children go to school</i>

00:24:42.012 --> 00:24:44.182
<i> and so it was very
 uplifting after such,</i>

00:24:44.182 --> 00:24:45.883
after many,
many months of hatred,

00:24:45.883 --> 00:24:48.586
many, many months of pain,
many, many months of killing.

00:24:48.586 --> 00:24:50.187
I was starting to see

00:24:50.187 --> 00:24:53.358
the population that I'd known
10 years ago in Bangui.

00:24:53.358 --> 00:24:56.394
I saw the people that were
making the butterflies.

00:24:56.394 --> 00:24:57.695
I saw the laughter again.

00:24:57.695 --> 00:25:00.098
I saw the children
playing football again.

00:25:01.232 --> 00:25:04.469
<i> All guarded by
 now the Cameroon military</i>

00:25:04.469 --> 00:25:07.705
<i> so that the anti-balaka
 don't come across and start</i>

00:25:07.705 --> 00:25:09.540
<i>attacking the local population.</i>

00:25:10.508 --> 00:25:13.411
<i> The children, some of them go
 to school for the first time.</i>

00:25:14.845 --> 00:25:16.414
<i> And they now live as
 they lived in</i>

00:25:16.414 --> 00:25:19.451
<i> Central African Republic
 in these camps in CAR.</i>

00:25:19.451 --> 00:25:20.684
And the UNHCR,

00:25:20.684 --> 00:25:22.320
United Nations High Commissions
for Refugees

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:24.855
is doing actually a really
interesting... a really good job

00:25:24.855 --> 00:25:27.358
of integrating the
refugee population

00:25:27.358 --> 00:25:31.295
with the local
Cameroonian population

00:25:31.295 --> 00:25:34.732
so that... there is very little
animosity between the two.

00:25:34.732 --> 00:25:38.236
So they go into
a town and they bore

00:25:38.236 --> 00:25:41.439
10 or 15 wells,
they create 10 or 15 wells

00:25:41.439 --> 00:25:42.841
for the whole population,

00:25:42.841 --> 00:25:44.108
not just for the
refugee population

00:25:44.108 --> 00:25:45.543
but for the whole population.

00:25:45.543 --> 00:25:46.911
They build schools
for the whole population,

00:25:46.911 --> 00:25:48.379
not just for the
refugee population.

00:25:48.379 --> 00:25:50.781
So in a way they are
learning their lessons,

00:25:50.781 --> 00:25:52.583
they're becoming
better in what they do

00:25:52.583 --> 00:25:53.918
and this is a great example.

00:25:53.918 --> 00:25:56.154
We were very encouraged by
what we saw there.

00:25:56.888 --> 00:25:58.522
<i> There is a lot
 of talk about return,</i>

00:25:58.522 --> 00:26:00.124
<i> like when can these
 people return.</i>

00:26:00.124 --> 00:26:02.159
<i>But I asked all of these people</i>

00:26:02.193 --> 00:26:03.695
<i> when did they want to return,</i>

00:26:03.695 --> 00:26:06.464
<i> if they wanted to return and
 no one wanted to return.</i>

00:26:06.464 --> 00:26:08.432
<i> No one needed to return.</i>

00:26:08.432 --> 00:26:11.770
<i>And this is a really interesting
 concept for refugees,</i>

00:26:11.770 --> 00:26:13.939
<i> should we force them,
 at some point to return?</i>

00:26:13.939 --> 00:26:16.374
<i> Should we be really
 be working for that end?</i>

00:26:16.374 --> 00:26:17.609
<i> And this is a really
 interesting question</i>

00:26:17.609 --> 00:26:20.144
<i> that we still don't
 know the answer to.</i>

00:26:20.144 --> 00:26:22.413
<i> Thank you very much
 indeed for listening</i>

00:26:22.413 --> 00:26:24.249
( applause )

00:26:24.249 --> 00:26:27.519
( outro music )

